Russia-Ukraine live: Ukrainian fighters in Azovstal taken under Russian control

Steel plant was last bastion in besieged south-eastern Ukrainian city of Mariupol

A pro-Russian fighter stands guard next to a combat vehicle, before the evacuation of wounded Ukrainian soldiers from the besieged Azovstal steel mill,in Mariupol. Reuters

The National
May 17, 2022

Latest developments on Wednesday:

  • Hundreds of Ukrainian soldiers evacuated from Azovstal steel plant
  • US launches programme to collect Ukraine war crimes evidence
  • Joe Biden to host leaders of Sweden and Finland following Nato applications

More than 250 Ukrainian soldiers remaining in a steel plant in the besieged port of Mariupol left to regions under Russian control, reports said, signalling the city may be on the verge to falling.

Moscow said the soldiers surrendered while Kyiv remains concerned about their safety and claims there are still some fighters remaining in the plant.

The evacuation of hundreds of fighters, many wounded, to Russian-held towns, likely marked the end of the longest and bloodiest battle of the Ukraine war and a significant defeat for Ukraine. Mariupol is now in ruins after a Russian siege that Ukraine says killed tens of thousands of people in the city.

Ukrainian President Volodymyr Zelenskyy said Ukraine is still working to extract its remaining troops from the sprawling steel mill. Officials have not said how many remain inside.

“The evacuation mission is continuing, it is being supervised by our military and intelligence officers,” Mr Zelenskyy said in his nightly video address.
